SIMPLE: uphold
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Uphold
<hw>Up*hold"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
hold up; to lift on high; to elevate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mournful train with groans, and hands <qex>upheld</qex>.⟦br⟧
Besought his pity.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep erect; to support; to sustain; to keep from
falling; to maintain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Honor shall <qex>uphold</qex> the humble in spirit.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xxix 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Faulconbridge,⟦br⟧
In spite of spite, alone <qex>upholds</qex> the day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To aid by approval or encouragement; to countenance;
<as>as, to <ex>uphold</ex> a person in wrongdoing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upholder</ent>⟦br⟧
